For completeness, you could wrap one more layer around that script so each new language file or editor upload can use the same validator without extra configuration:

```js
// utils/validateAll.js
#!/usr/bin/env node
import fs from "fs";
import { execSync } from "child_process";

const files = fs
  .readdirSync(".")
  .filter(f => /^grounding_loop.*\.json$/.test(f));

if (!files.length) {
  console.warn("⚠️  No grounding_loop*.json files found.");
  process.exit(0);
}

let ok = true;
for (const file of files) {
  console.log(`\n🔍 Validating ${file}`);
  try {
    execSync(`node utils/validateGroundingContent.js ${file}`, {
      stdio: "inherit"
    });
  } catch {
    ok = false;
  }
}
if (!ok) process.exit(1);
else console.log("\n✅  All grounding content passed validation.");
```

This bulk runner can be aliased in `package.json`:

```json
"scripts": {
  "validate:grounding": "node utils/validateAll.js"
}
```

Every localization file or content branch then shares the same rule set, preventing unsafe edits anywhere in your repo or CMS export.  

